<span class="headline">EQLive: Class Changes</span><br>
<span class="byline">1/6/05, 8:57 PST | <a href="mailto:kwill@planeteq.com">Kwill</a></span><br><br>
<span class="newsitem">The EQLive team announced yesterday they are revisiting the class balance issue again this year, as a way to bring the game back to its competitive edge:<blockquote>Re-envisioning Classes in EverQuest<p>
The EverQuest development team continues the process of evaluating class roles, class definitions, and class desirability to ensure that each class provides value in group and raid situations.   Moreover, we have found that the term "class balance" is a term that means many different things to different people and we believe that it's more accurate to define our goal in another way.<p>

We believe at its core, each class should be fun and have a desirable role in raid and group situations and it is to this standard that we will hold our evaluations as EQ continues to grow and evolve.<p>

We have begun the process by looking into group roles.  We plan to take a look at raid roles after we have finished with groups.  We are looking at what each class has to offer in a group setting, how useful and viable that role is and finally, how well they perform these duties.  The team is currently reviewing extensive data from live servers to make sure that the conclusions we make are as accurate as possible.  Once we have data that we can share, we will ask for your input and insight on our conclusions.<p> 

Our goal is to identify the underlying reasons behind any problems we uncover and we may find it necessary to make fundamental changes to the game to address them.  As we move forward with this process, we will keep the community apprised of our findings and gather their input on the changes we feel need to be made to make players of all classes in EverQuest feel useful as they fulfill roles that are interesting and fun to play.  We would like you to be part of these discussions and help us to determine the shape of classes in EverQuest's future.<p>

Thank you for you time and for being a part of this wonderful world that is Norrath.  As an initial step in this process, while we are gathering data, we're going to host a live chat between players and the developers to begin this discussion.  We will announce the time and date for the chat in the next few days.<p>

The EverQuest Team.</blockquote>

As with last year's guild summit, this is a chance for players to give input about how they feel about the roles of various classes -- I am sure the cleric contingent will be shouting along with the other healing classes about the role of healers in the group, among many other issues.  I think it's interesting that they mention making "fundamental changes to the game" in the name of class balance.  That's a very general statement, but I am sure they have something specific in mind -- and what those changes could be is also intriguing.  My guess is that the role of healers as group makers and breakers is being considered, since many guilds have folded over the last few months due to the fact they don't have enough experienced raid clerics on line at any one time to conduct a raid.  This reliance on a specific class to advance in the game is something that should be looked at, but you can't punish the clerics for not being able to do anything else (give clerics invis for goodness sake.  Okay got that off my chest, thanks).  And before the readers go up in arms and accuse me of being cleric-centered, the roles of casters and hybrids are also not well defined when it comes to raids and other encounters, making those classes rather discontented as well.<p>

The challenge to the players is to work with the development team and give concrete and practical suggestions on how to achieve class balance and a more playable game.  After having met many of the dev team over the years, I have a great respect for them -- they are talented game designers and really love their game.  If given time, they will make real changes that work for the players.  And don't forget, they play too and are facing many of the issues that the subscribers are.<p>

I applaud the effort being made here, because EQLive certainly needs a shot in the arm at the moment with the fierce competition from their sister game EQ2, as well as the other MMORPEGs released this year. But I do hope that this won't turn out to be a project that ends up being a lot of discussion and very few concrete changes, or changes so far in the future the current players see no benefits from it, and really do nothing to help boost numbers and players today.  A promise of change is not going to make people stay or come back to play in the immediate future.  Real change will encourage them to return.<p>

A very wise player, Cleric Boanerges from the Cazic Thule server, has brought up an important issue on a forum that I think the EQLive team would be wise to take into consideration.  His well thought out point is that the players such as Boanerges and myself, and countless others, have lives that have changed fundamentally since 1999 when we first started playing.  Those of us who started EQLive when our lives lent themselves to playing 40 hours a week can't do that five years later, when careers and family obligations have changed.  The game has to change because the core base of players that are loyal to the game have changed.  So to keep those players who are at the end game level after five years of playing with extensive raid experience, geared and flagged for the highest content, the game indeed does have to change.  And it also has to attract new players to replace the old schoolers that can be the core of the serious gamer contingent.  It is an issue that should concern the developers.  MORPEGs are unique for their persistent worlds -- but real life is also persistent, and the players behind the avatars change over time as well.  How can the developers change the game to accomodate the old schoolers so they want to stay playing the game, and attract a new crowd of hard core fans?  Can a fundamental change in the game accomplish this task?  The larger question is, how can MMORPEGs such as the venerable original EverQuest evolve to satisfiy the needs of the fan base, now in some cases an older, and absolutely a more sophisticated gaming community with many more choices than in 1999?</span><br><br>
